commentText: Retired LEO, 25 years. I left in disgust with my department and the profession as a whole. I've read a lot of comments about senior command staff being the biggest problem. I totally agree. The world thinks so much of police, but they have no idea what it is really like. They have no idea what people will do to each other to get promoted,  to get that special detail, to get that detective position. People would always say to me, "you guys don't get paid enough..." You are correct. But not for the reasons you think. I carried a gun, wore body armor and was trained to deal with all sorts of threats from domestic encounters, three hundred pound drunks, meth heads and active shooters. But there is no armor, no training that can protect you from a weaponized administration. The world would be shocked at the things I have seen.  But now I have a nice job and get a check every month from my department's retirement that reminds me that I don't have those problems any more.   All the best, young lady.  You got out alive.

commentText: Ive lived in CT my whole life, and when i was 20 i worked at a gas stationas an assistant manager. One day my boss put a hiring sign in the front window and i asked her how many people we were loking to hire. She told me zero. Appsrently around 2010 CT created a law stating that all companies had to advertise that they were hiring. Part of that law was that no one could be denied an application if the store used paper ones, if not you had to explain to the person how to apply online. It was supposedly meant to help decrease all types of prejudice during the hiring process. It made no sense to me because if a manager was prejudice, that persn they didnt like would never make it past the first interview. Anyways, all it did was fool people into thinking we were actually hiring when we werent. It wasted everyone involved time. I tried explaining the law to people when they would come back in or call about the application they dropped off weeks ago. People were pissed. I was mad because i had to keep dealing with everyone who was upset.

commentText: Part of it, I believe I've heard, is to make it look like they are hiring, even getting applications, so when an employee asks for a raise, they can point to the listings only to say that they have hundreds of people looking to get the employee's job. That they should be grateful for what they have and that they can replace them on a whim. Sure, they possibly could, however, that doesn't account for training, the risk of a new hire possibly not fitting in or being even more of a pain to work with, and they already have as few people hired as possible, so they don't want to fire you, because even if they get a replacement, that's a role that's not going to be functioning properly, if at all for a while when you're gone. But they can always threaten you and make you feel replaceable so you don't ask for a raise, or potentially even take a pay cut.  Manipulation is standard practice in a capitalist system.

commentText: If you are applying for jobs you should expect 9 out of 10 jobs to be ghost jobs or required postings. If the job has little more then a title, likely a ghost job. If the posting has a very eclectic mix of requirements likely a required post tailored to the person pre-selected to fill it. If a generally cohesive wish list with few requirements, that likely a real job. General 10-20 applications per interview and 10-20 interviews to get hired. I have successfully done this 3 times, once for an entry level job and twice for student level jobs. All the other jobs used industry contacts, recruiters, and general back channel shenanigans. If you are not networking it's almost impossible to get employed üòï And at some point when you get higher in your career they don't post jobs or even have them. It is more about having a contact in a company that is growing and can create a position for you. But that's VP level positions and while I have had spots created for me it is not common at my level and some of that may have, honestly, been DEI opportunity for the company.

videoTitle: how we‚Äôre *actually* getting jobs in 2025 #jobsearch
commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.

Last season showed that replacements mattered, and this year must be an upgrade to make up for that loss. Championship programs reload with experience, not experiments. SEC-tested coaches understand recruiting battles, physical football, and playoff pressure ‚Äî exactly what Texas needs to take the next step. If Sark wants to capitalize on the talent on the roster and the future with Arch Manning, surrounding him with battle-tested coaches is non-negotiable. videoDescription: In this episode, we investigate the connection between the Texas Hill Country flood disaster and the impact of DEI hiring policies ...
commentText: I understand the frustration people are feeling after the flood, but I think we‚Äôre jumping too quickly to blame DEI. DEI wasn‚Äôt created to lower standards, it was created because, historically, not everyone even got a fair shot. It‚Äôs not just about race, it‚Äôs also about gender, disability, and making sure people from all backgrounds can succeed based on merit. Blaming DEI anytime something goes wrong is a slippery slope, especially if the root cause is more complex than just who got hired. DEI is a result of people going years being overlooked, excluded, and denied chances. DEI is more than just including people, it drives real improvement. Studies show diverse teams make better decisions, boost innovation, and lead to stronger financial performance. It helps companies attract top talent, reduce turnover, and connect with broader markets. When done right, DEI creates fair opportunities for everyone, not by lowering standards, but by removing unfair barriers so the most qualified people can thrive, regardless of race, gender, or background. I‚Äôd rather know who hired him and why? Without that info it‚Äôs just assumptions. DEI has nothing on knowing the people that are hiring these days. That‚Äôs not a DEI hire, that‚Äôs a ‚Äúoh we know you, ‚Äúyou can have the job.‚ÄùüòÇ That‚Äôs a Lebron doing for Bronny move, Favoritism and connections win out most of the time. The DEI law has nothing to do with what people themselves decide to do morally. DEI and nepotism are two very different things, that‚Äôs my opinion. DEI is meant to cancel out nepotism. It can change the law, but it can‚Äôt change people‚Äôs hearts and morals.
